<div id='communityQuestionsWithAnswers'>
<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/1338816-how-do-you-think-why-the-book-is-called">How do you think, why the book is called &quot;The Ruins&quot;, if the ruins don&#39;t play any role in the story?</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_1338816'><a id="like_count_community_question_1338816" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/1338816?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">1 like</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F1150339.The_Ruins">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/1338816-how-do-you-think-why-the-book-is-called">3 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/1338816-how-do-you-think-why-the-book-is-called">See all 7 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/7192627-robert-spencer"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1324020139i/7192627.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/7192627-robert-spencer">Robert Spencer</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
This answer contains spoilers…
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[
  
    Yeah, I guess it's because there ARE ruins there, they just haven't been excavated. Most of the famous ruins in Mexico and Guatemala were underground <a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">…more</a>
    Yeah, I guess it's because there ARE ruins there, they just haven't been excavated. Most of the famous ruins in Mexico and Guatemala were underground before archaeologists uncovered them. I mean, Mexico has the world's biggest ancient pyramid (bigger than the Great Pyramid of Khufu in Giza) in a place called Cholula, but it's unexcavated as it's underneath a Spanish colonial church (the Spaniards thought they were just building it on a hill).<br />So, the fact this thing is growing out of a mesoamerican ruin offers some tantalising possibilities as to its origin. Something to do with the ancient Mayan religion, perhaps? Is it even a plant, or some kind of Lovecraftian horror that, like an iceberg, stretches deep underground, and the "vines" are its sensory organs?<br />I loved the mystery of this book, as well as the deep horror!<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">(less)</a>
  
 <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerFooter'>

