    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2934722449" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2934722449" />
    <a title="Ɗẳɳ  2.☊" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12058788-2"><img alt="Ɗẳɳ  2.☊" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1589380555p2/12058788.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2934722449?book_show_action=true">Aug 23, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ɗẳɳ  2.☊" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ɗẳɳ  2.☊" href="/user/show/12058788-2">Ɗẳɳ  2.☊</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9781400043873" href="/book/show/21726.The_Ruins">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12058788-2?shelf=horror">horror</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12058788-2?shelf=buddy-reads">buddy-reads</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2934722449" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9392146531163094226"><b>★★★☆☆½</b><br/><br/>Always be prepared—the motto drilled into ever Boy Scout’s head from day one—never much crossed the minds of the group of twentysomethings heading out into the jungles of Mexico. A group of friends and recent acquaintances gathered together early one morning on a mission to track down a kid brother who’s runoff after a girl. <br/><br/>They’ve got to get a move on if they want to catch that bus to Coba, but their tails are dragging after a late night of drinking. From Coba, it’s another eleven grueli</span>
  <span id="freeText9392146531163094226" style="display:none"><b>★★★☆☆½</b><br><br>Always be prepared—the motto drilled into ever Boy Scout’s head from day one—never much crossed the minds of the group of twentysomethings heading out into the jungles of Mexico. A group of friends and recent acquaintances gathered together early one morning on a mission to track down a kid brother who’s runoff after a girl. <br><br>They’ve got to get a move on if they want to catch that bus to Coba, but their tails are dragging after a late night of drinking. From Coba, it’s another eleven grueling miles to the ruins of the archeological dig site where the brother went, according to the hand-drawn map. Even so, they ought to be able to get there and back in a day, two at most, so what does it matter if they forget to pack a few necessities? What’s the worst that can happen?<br><br>They hardly know Mathais, but can’t help but feel for his plight—his brother should have been back weeks ago, and if he doesn’t return soon he’ll miss his flight home. But, in the back of their minds, they’re also thinking a day trip to the jungle might actually be a nice change of scenery, a break from the monotony of the beach and hotel, an adventure. <br><br>But now that they’re on their way, so far off the beaten path, they’re beginning to rethink things. Why was that cab driver acting so sketchy? And how are they supposed to get back to town once they find his brother? The odds of another car passing down that rutted, overgrown, back road seem pretty slim. And what’s with those kids and their mangy mutt tailing them, all of a sudden? Where the hell are these ruins anyway? This is turning into way move of a hike then they planned for and this sweltering heat is fucking brutal—pass the tequila, Pablo. <br><br>Not everyone was on board to begin with, but, once they reach that strange hill covered in beautiful red flowering vines, there’s no turning back. They’ve unwittingly stumbled upon an ancient evil, and the only way out of this nightmare is through. Lucky they came prepared . . . <br><br>This was a “hold my hand, cover my eyes, don't leave me,” buddy-read with Delee and a few friends because, according to her, some books are tooooooo scaaaaaary to read alone. So I was happy to oblige and chime in every now and again about the things that annoyed me.<br><br>Namely, how most of the group acted like children, passively hoping whatever they found too horrible to contemplate might simply go away if they closed their eyes long enough. Desperately clinging to the hope that help was on the way rather than doing anything to improve their situation. So overwhelmed they couldn’t possibly think for themselves, but had to rely on Jeff to do all their thinking and planning for them. And it’s not like he was some rocket scientist or wilderness expert—<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[he sports a Hulk avatar for God’s sake! <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> In fact, some of his ideas were pretty extreme, considering they’d only been stranded for a couple of days. And it was absolutely amazing how quickly the group crumbled under pressure. Pathetic is the only word for it.<br><br><b>He knew he was supposed to go help her now, wipe her clean like an infant, guide her back into the tent. But this was her own fault, wasn’t it? So why should he be the one to pick up the pieces? He wasn’t going to do it. He was going to let her lie there, let her wake at dawn with vomit caked to her face.</b> <br><br>That said I thought the vine itself was a clever and unique creation. The way it slowly revealed its impressive assortment of talents to torment and fuck with the castaways’ heads was a thing of beauty. I couldn’t help but picture it as a sentient, single organism—a catlike alien creature perhaps—that enjoyed playing with its food . . . <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1566575916i/28039784.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Poor Goose, if only they’d offered you a more formidable opponent than these idiots, we might have been in for a real treat.</["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></span>
  <a data-text-id="9392146531163094226" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


