  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_193623388" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/193623388" />
    <a title="K.D. Absolutely" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2156200-k-d-absolutely"><img alt="K.D. Absolutely" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1471967140p2/2156200.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/193623388?book_show_action=true">Aug 02, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="K.D. Absolutely" class="user" itemprop="url" name="K.D. Absolutely" href="/user/show/2156200-k-d-absolutely">K.D. Absolutely</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780307389718" href="/book/show/1942503.The_Ruins">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Jzhunagev</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2156200-k-d-absolutely?shelf=horror">horror</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer193623388&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer193623388" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14361095993867120383">This is my Halloween read for this year and it is very apt because it is really, really scary. While reading that part when the killer vine is going inside the body of its prey, I thought I could feel my limbs or my abdominal cavity constricting as if I could feel something slithering under my skin and putting pressure on my muscles. I thought I could feel the cool misty feel of the forest, smell the musky trees, hear the crowning cocks and chirping birds and see the sun going down and darkness </span>
  <span id="freeText14361095993867120383" style="display:none">This is my Halloween read for this year and it is very apt because it is really, really scary. While reading that part when the killer vine is going inside the body of its prey, I thought I could feel my limbs or my abdominal cavity constricting as if I could feel something slithering under my skin and putting pressure on my muscles. I thought I could feel the cool misty feel of the forest, smell the musky trees, hear the crowning cocks and chirping birds and see the sun going down and darkness slowly spreading in the sky turning the Mayan sacred hill into a graveyard full of immaculate white bones underneath the vines and beautiful purple flowers. What I am saying is that every page this book is truly engaging as it makes sure that your senses are busy working while reading. Imagining being in a forest is something that is easy for me to do because I grew up in an island in the Pacific when the vegetations in our coconut plantations were still thick and I used to walk in the rice/corn fields enjoying the morning mists or help my father in clearing up weeds and vines in between the mature coconut trees. <br /><br />I neither have not read <b>Scott B. Smith’s </b> (born 1965) earlier hit, <i>A Simple Plan</i> nor have seen the movie adaptation of that or this <i>The Ruins</i> so I did not have any expectation prior to cracking this book open. With one exception: A good GR friend rated this with “1” star and I think that the disappointment was due to the fact that she had read and enjoyed <i>A Simple Plan</i> and reasonably expected that this book was at par with that earlier work. So, I said I would put this book last in my tbr and I did not plan to read this soon. It was just that I got bored with Stephen King’s <i>It</i> and I needed to have a Halloween read. I needed to feel scared and get in tune with this season.<br /><br />I thought this was a good pick. It’s just that when I was finally done reading the book, I asked myself: so, <i>is there any lesson or any learning or any new knowledge that I learned from this work?</i> The resounding answer: <b>none.</b> It is all about being scared. It is an escapist book. It enables you to escape into another place and although you enjoy the scare, you bring back nothing. Definitely no takeaway. Mayan? It is an extinct tribe and Smith did not bother to mention anything regarding their history. Cancun? Easy, it is a place in Mexico. Four young single Americans vacationing in there? No brainer. Americans go everywhere they find interesting. Friendships among those four? They are so stupid they almost killed each other. The two brainless girls alternately saying <i>”bitch”</i> and <i>”slut”</i> to each other was even copied by the more intelligent killer vine. Oh, the killer vine? If Cormac McCarthy’s <i>The Road</i> makes us aware that we need to take care of our environment, Scott B. Smith’s <i>The Ruins</i> makes us want to hate forest because it is only in the forest where there are huge trees with vines. Nothing. Nada. It is like watching those B-grade horror flicks with thin plots where nothing is happening except that each of the characters has to die. You shout. You hyperventilate. You cringe on your seat. You cower in fear. You keep your eyes covered. But as you step out from the movie house, you feel cheated as you did not get any lesson from it. No lesson that could turn you into a better person. Waste of time. Waste of your hard-earned money. <br /><br />But it is Halloween and I surely got that spirit of the season with this book. So, for Smith’s effort, I thought this deserves my two stars.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14361095993867120383" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review193623388">
  <td colspan="2">
